Now if he chooses to buy things at the efficient price and sell at an absurdly high price, he'll price himself out of the market.  It will just cause him to dump assloads of plat into buying stuff, which will raise the efficient market price slightly, but not to nearly as high a level as he is trying to sell it at.  This will just cause him to burn plat while he attempts to artificially bolster the market price on the items.  Eventually he runs out of plat as no one has an infinite amount, the demand curve shifts down drastically and quickly, and now he's sitting on merchandise that cost him maybe 500kpp and is worth about 100kpp.  So he's just lost a ton of plat.<br>
<br>
It's something like the devaluation of the Thai Bhat in the summer of 1998.  Thailand was pegging the currency.  This means that in order to keep the price of the Thai Bhat higher than it was suppoed to be in an efficient market, they were buying Thai Bhat at a fixed (pegged) amount of dollars.  For a time this kept the currency at a fixed and stable value.  However, maintaining this cost the country a lot of money.  In the end, they ran out and couldn't sustain it, so they had to announce the currency would go unpegged and would be subject to market forces.  The Bhat devalued to by something huge like 80 percent in a matter of a day and the country of Thailand had just burned through massive cash reserves in the process, doing no one any good.<br>
<br>
There is really nothing to worry about, people cannot sustain a market shift on any items unless they have a monopoly on the supply or demand of/for that item, which is not the case for this guy.  If his pricing is really as absurd as you all seem to think (and I agree) just give him a bit of time and he'll end up broke.<br>
